Summary
Turkey sees the South Caucasus among strategic in the hierarchy of the goals and interests of the
current political ideology formed by the ruling Justice and Development Party. The region – along
with Central Asia – has been of strategic importance for Turkey since the Ottoman Empire period.
It is the Caucasus that Russia, Turkey and Iran have been competing throughout history. And this
conflicting interaction in the South Caucasus continues behind the curtain of world politics in the 21st
century with a number of non-regional actors involved. After the dissolution of the USSR the South
Caucasus states have become subjects in international relations, however, they have not turned into
full actors in the modern world politics. Despite their efforts to develop their own independent policies,
they remain under the influence of regional and world powers, Turkey being one of most important.
The article studies the Turkish policy towards Azerbaijan, Armenia and Georgia, and analyzes its
concept and realization taking into consideration specific features of the Ankara relations with Baku,
Erevan and Tbilisi. The author makes a conclusion on the importance of the region in the course
of the Turkish self-positioning in world politics and prospects of the Turkish policies in the South
Caucasus considering Ankara’s achievements in its activities on the governmental and social levels
within the framework of the ‘Zero problems with neighbors’ foreign political concept.
Key Words: Turkish foreign policy, ‘Zero problems with neighbors’, Turkish policy in the South
Caucasus, Turkish-Azerbaijani relations, Turkish-Georgian relations, Turkish-Armenian relations.
